Q1. Write a query to display:
Employee Name
Department Name
Only matching records.

	SELECT e.Name, d.DepartmentName 
	FROM Employees e
	JOIN Departments d ON 
		e.DepartmentID = d.DepartmentID;

Q2. Display:
Employee Name
Department Name
Return all employees, even if a department is missing.

	SELECT e.Name, d.DepartmentName
	FROM Employees e
	LEFT JOIN Departments d ON 
		e.DepartmentID = d.DepartmentID;

Q3. Display:
Employee Name
Department Name
Return all departments, even if no employee belongs to them.

	SELECT e.Name, d.DepartmentName
	FROM Employees e
	RIGHT JOIN Departments d ON e.DepartmentID = d.DepartmentID;

Q4. Display all employees who do not have a matching department.
Use LEFT JOIN
Look for NULL values in the department table.

	SELECT e.Name, d.DepartmentName
	FROM Employees e
	LEFT JOIN Departments d 
		ON e.DepartmentID = d.DepartmentID
	WHERE DepartmentName IS NULL;

Q5. Show all departments that have no employees.
Use RIGHT JOIN or LEFT JOIN
Check for NULL on the employee side.

	SELECT d.DepartmentName 
	FROM Employees e
	RIGHT JOIN Departments d 
		ON e.DepartmentID = d.DepartmentID
	WHERE e.Name IS NULL;
